When flattening a `Sprite`, `forceTinted` is not set on any of the `QuadBatche`s created, which is effect creates too many batches. Also `forceTinted` is not copied when cloning a batch.

A fix is simple:

```
@@ -148,6 +148,7 @@ package starling.display
             clone.mSyncRequired = true;
             clone.blendMode = blendMode;
             clone.alpha = alpha;
+            clone.forceTinted = forceTinted;
             return clone;
         }

@@ -535,6 +536,10 @@ package starling.display
             var batch:QuadBatch = object as QuadBatch;
             var filter:FragmentFilter = object.filter;

+            var profile:String = Starling.current.profile;
+            var forceTinted:Boolean = (profile != "baselineConstrained" && profile != "baseline");
+            var newQuadBatch:QuadBatch;
+
             if (quadBatchID == -1)
             {
                 isRootObject = true;
@@ -542,8 +547,14 @@ package starling.display
                 objectAlpha = 1.0;
                 blendMode = object.blendMode;
                 ignoreCurrentFilter = true;
-                if (quadBatches.length == 0) quadBatches.push(new QuadBatch());
-                else quadBatches[0].reset();
+                if (quadBatches.length == 0) {
+                    newQuadBatch = new QuadBatch();
+                    newQuadBatch.forceTinted = forceTinted;
+                    quadBatches.push(newQuadBatch);
+                }
+                else {
+                    quadBatches[0].reset();
+                }
             }
             else
             {
@@ -614,12 +625,16 @@ package starling.display
                 }

                 quadBatch = quadBatches[quadBatchID];
-                
-                if (quadBatch.isStateChange(tinted, alpha*objectAlpha, texture, 
+
+                if (quadBatch.isStateChange(tinted, alpha*objectAlpha, texture,
                                             smoothing, blendMode, numQuads))
                 {
                     quadBatchID++;
-                    if (quadBatches.length <= quadBatchID) quadBatches.push(new QuadBatch());
+                    if (quadBatches.length <= quadBatchID) {
+                        newQuadBatch = new QuadBatch();
+                        newQuadBatch.forceTinted = forceTinted;
+                        quadBatches.push(newQuadBatch);
+                    }
                     quadBatch = quadBatches[quadBatchID];
                     quadBatch.reset();
                 }
```

As a side note, I noticed that even with this fix quads with `blendMode` set to `BlendMode.AUTO` are batched on a separate batch, which makes sense (maybe sprites parent is responsible for setting the right `blendMode`), but it would be great to, just for convenience, be able to override `BlendMode.AUTO` on all batched children with a mode passed to `flatten()`, e.g.:

``` as3
sprite.flatten(false, BlendMode.NORMAL);
```

Hello, I really love Adobe Air and Starling. Starling is easy to use, simple and fast framework.
But, unfortunately, in some games, where I need to control over 5000 objects (only Starling, no physics engine), starling becomes a bit slower. I get stable ~30fps. And I ported my game to SpriteKit. I'm currently using SpriteKit the first time. I would like to see some of advantages of it and my requests in Starling in future versions.
1. By default, touch handler is disabled.
2. Calling functions instead of dispatching events:
   for example

``` actionscript
class MySprite extends Sprite {
override public function touchBegan(touches:Vector.<Touch>):void {...}
override public function touchMoved(touches:Vector.<Touch>):void {...}
override public function touchEnded(touches:Vector.<Touch>):void {...}
override public function enterFrame(time:int):void {... }
override public function addedToStage(parent:DisplayObject):void {...}
...
```

or using interfaces

``` actionscript
interface ITouchCalls {
function get touchable():Boolean;
function touchBegan(touches:Vector.<Touch>):void;
function touchMoved(touches:Vector.<Touch>):void;
function touchEnd(touches:Vector.<Touch>):void;
}

interface IRenderCalls {
function enterFrame(time:int):void;
}

interface IStageCalls {
function addedToStage(parent:DisplayObject):void;
function removedFromStage():void;
}
```

I think using interfaces makes  objects more flexible and customizable. So I can add only functions that I use.

``` actionscript
class PlayButton extends Image implements ITouchCalls { ... }
class Enemy extends Image implements IStageCalls, IRenderCalls { ... }
```

3 . `addChild()` must throw error if displayobject has a parent. For sorting the hierarchy use `zIndex`
4 . Default settings architecture:

``` actionscript
class TextureMipMapping {
static const DEFAULT:int = -1;
static const FALSE: 0;
static const TRUE:int = 1;
}

class TextureScale {
static const DEFAULT:Number = Number.NaN;
}
```

``` actionscript
...
//Setting default variables
Starling.TextureMipMap = TextureMipMapping.FALSE;
Starling.TextureScale = 3.0;
starling = new Starling(...);
...

//Image texture has no mip and scaled to 1/3;
var image = new Image(Texture.fromEmbeddedAsset(SomeClass));

//image2 texture has no mip and scaled to 1/2;
var image2 = new Image(Texture.fromEmbeddedAsset(SomeClass, TextureMipMapping.DEFAULT, 2));

//image3 texture has mip and scaled to 1/3
